entry.title: Have automatic beacons sent from ctrl+click.
entry.content:
When a user ctrl+clicks a link to open a page in a new tab, the signals

that are currently checked for automatic beacons (initiator user

activation + initiator activation status in the navigation request

params) to determine if there is user activation are not set. This

causes a beacon to fail to send.



This CL modifies the automatic beacons user activation check to also

check if the `was_activated` flag was set in the commit params. This

flag is set explicitly for cases like ctrl+clicking a link[1].



This CL also adds a new internal WPT to test this case. We are using an

internal WPT instead of an external WPT to get access to the

`eventSender` class, which supports sending ctrl/cmd+click events.

FLEDGE-related helpers from the fenced frame external WPT folder are

brought in so that we can run ad auctions and check automatic beacon

reporting.



[1]https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/renderer_host/navigation_request.cc;l=3981-3986;drc=892166276bba156857c6321a1c5035c83200b55b

We currently treat QR code verification as a sequential step after the

remote source device initiates the connection with the target device. But according to our PRD, we need to render the QR Code as the initial

PRD requirements. PIN Code verification must remain as a sequential

step after the connection is initiated due to the auth code it depends

on.

entry.title: [IP Protection] Don't use PKSF in *auth_token_getter_unittest.cc
entry.content:
I added use of the IpProtectionAuthTokenGetterFactory to

ip_protection_auth_token_getter_unittest.cc so that we could

create IpProtectionAuthTokenGetters more closely to how we would

in real code. However, this has some downsides. Specifically:



- it's tricky to set the feature flag state before the

IpProtectionAuthTokenGetterFactory ProfileKeyedServiceFactory (PKSF)

is created (here's how we do it in unit tests for that [1]). As a

result, we were seeing lots of flakiness on some Android bots [2].



- we can't use IdentityTestEnvironment directly like the docs

recommend [3]



Let's just not do that anymore. :)

Sometimes these keys come from the untrusted renderer. Try to catch

If some cases slip through, it's better to CHECK than DCHECK. In

other cases, the key will have been generated by browser code. These

would be bugs.



The fuzzer is modified to not send invalid keys to the encode function.

entry.title: Avoid dangling pointer in AffiliatedMatchHelper.
entry.content:
AffiliatedMatchHelper keeps a pointer to the AffiliationService that

can became dangling in two cases:

1) In a unit test in which the AffiliationService was manually destroyed

prior to destroying the AffiliatedMatchHelper.

2) In a browsertest in which a mock factory function was injected into

the AffiliationServiceFactory. In this case the following happened:

During startup, the keyed services AffiliationsService and the

PasswordStore(s) are created, with the PasswordStore service

depending on the AffiliationService. Among other things, a

PasswordStore owns an AffiliatedMatchHelper, which keeps a raw_ptr

to the AffiliationService.

The WellKnownChangePasswordNavigationThrottleBrowsertest then

injected a mock factory function, leading to the destruction of the

already created AffiliationService to which PasswordStore's

AffiliatedMatchHelper keeps a raw_ptr. Thus, the raw_ptr becomes

dangling.



Case 1) is fixed by resetting the AffiliatedMatchHelper prior to

resetting the AffiliationService

Case 2) is fixed by injecting the mock factory functions prior to

service startup so that no real AffiliationService is ever created.



Since the fix to 2) required rewriting parts of the browser test,

the CL also performs some cleanup, such as removing an unnecessary

intermediate base class.

entry.title: Allow PAA WPTs for Protected Audience to detect JavaScript errors
entry.content:
Create a report handler to receive message during protected audience

test cases. It only supports passing reports via parameters and the

reports are stored by uuid.



For the successful test cases, a sendReportTo()/reportAdAuctionWin()

is triggered after calling contributeToHistogram(). It will send a

report of the worklet's name to the report-lite server as the value in

the stash.



For the failure test cases, a sendReportTo()/reportAdAuctionWin() is

triggered when an exception is caught. The report format is same as

above.



At the end of each test case, there is a observe function which will

try to get the stashed reports by the uuid to check if the reports are

sent and stashed successfully to verify contributeToHistogram() is

entry.title: [Privacy Sandbox] Implement the loading of attestations list.
entry.content:
This CL implements the following:

1. When component updater signals the file is ready via

`ComponentReady()`, instruct it to invoke the callback, which is

`PrivacySandboxAttestations::LoadAttestations()`.

2. In this callback, it invokes `LoadAttestationsInternal()`

asynchronously on `base::SequencedTaskRunner`.

3. `LoadAttestationsInternal()` validates:

a) The map never exists, this is the first time it's ready or

b) The incoming version is newer than the existing one

Otherwise the file won't be opened and parsed.

4. Then it calls the parser to parse the input. It stores the result

to `PrivacySandboxAttestations` when the parsing is done.

5. Add unit tests.



Changed the async parsing to use `base::SequencedTaskRunner`, instead

of `base::ThreadPool`. The goal is to run parsing tasks in the posting

order.



A `base::SequencedTaskRunner` is created and owned by

`PrivacySandboxAttestations`. It is responsible for opening the file

as a `ifstream` and then parse it.



The final move assignment of the version and the attestations map is

done on UI thread. This is because queries on Privacy Sandbox APIs

attestation status may happen on the UI thread. Having it done on UI

thread can avoid potential race condition.



Moved the checks on whether to open the file and parsing to the start

of `PrivacySandboxAttestations::LoadAttestationsInternal()`. This

avoids opening the file then finds it no need to parse the list. For

example, when the incoming version is older, there is no need to parse

it, we keep the existing map.



In the next CL, a browser test will be added. After this CL is merged,

we will be able to manually verify that the component updater is

able to download the file and then load the attestations file to

the in-memory map via the callback.

entry.title: Store the COOP restrict crossOriginIsolated bit in policy container.
entry.content:
In https://crrev.com/c/4479858, we introduced a new boolean that

constrains whether an execution context can be considered

crossOriginIsolated. It is computed by the browser, depending on whether

the COOP origin matches the actual origin. This boolean is computed and

sent to the renderer at window creation time, or at commit time for

subframes. It causes breakage such as b/288962508 (Google

only) because SharedArrayBuffer's constructor sometimes needs to be

enabled earlier than CommitNavigation, which causes SharedArrayBuffer to

be undefined even though crossOriginIsolated is true.



This CL instead puts the boolean inside the policy container and lets it

handles inheritance.
